      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "uuid": "3b7a4fe0-163c-4491-9548-67991f681c67",
      "includes": [
        "media",
        "annotations",
        "label",
        "description"
      ],
      "start": 20,
      "end": 78,
      "file": "73e62492-bbe2-43b7-b0ca-f7e5c27a9835",
      "type": "event",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Latin Hip-Hop & ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        },
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Rap en Español ",
          "italic": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Dancehall's uptake in Panama and Puerto Rico was related to its counter-cultural connotations and close relationship with rap or hip-hop and thus sounds and images of modernity, urbanity, and Blackness. While roots reggae preached pan-African liberation, dancehall embraced more local concerns resonant with hip-hop: crime, drugs, violence, sex, poverty, and corruption. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "The proto-reggaetón of the early 1990s drew almost equally on reggae and hip-hop. The artists of this period—"
        },
        {
          "text": "raperos",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " or "
        },
        {
          "text": "rapeadores",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " not yet "
        },
        {
          "text": "reggaetoneros",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "—expressed more of an artistic alignment to hip-hop than reggae, in particular the gangster rap of the 1980s, as a major stylistic influence. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "However, the \"Latin Rap\" or rap in Spanish performed by Puerto Ricans in New York was also a major influence. This subgenre did not diverge stylistically so much as linguistically from hip-hop's sonic template. Puerto Rico's Vico C stands as a foundational figure here, as the artist who first demonstrated that one could rap entirely and compellingly in Spanish (aside from the occasional insertion of hip-hop slang lyrics) and therefore the founder of "
        },
        {
          "text": "rap en español",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": ". "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "uuid": "3f3d5d14-ea05-4bef-8482-64b52cbb0255",
      "includes": [
        "media",
        "annotations",
        "label",
        "description"
      ],
      "type": "event",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\"I sing hip-hop on top of a reggaetón beat. I don't know how to write it any other way\" (Tego Calderón, Marshall 2009 p. 27) "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Vico C describes reggaetón as \"essentially hip-hop, but with a flavor more compatible to the Caribbean\" (Chosen Few Documentary) "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Many interviewees in the Chosen Few documentary, for example, distinguish reggaeton from hip hop by noting that the former is more of a baile-centric genre, more appropriate for couple dancing that breaking, where focus is more on the beat than the lyrics. This comes directly from the genre's dancehall baseline and therefore overlap with a great number of Caribbean (dance) genres. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "horizontal-separator",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Afro-Panamanian ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        },
        {
          "textSize": "heading-three",
          "text": "Reggae en Español ",
          "italic": true
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Prior to the reggae's global rise in the 1970s when the genre found popularity outside major sites of Jamaican migration, Afro-Panamanian popular music was heavily based around calypso as performed by local favorites such as Lord Cobra and Lord Panama. By the late 1970s, roots reggae had largely supplanted calypso, largely in the urban contexts of Colón and Panama City. From here, artists such as El General, Nando Boom, and Chicho Man became the earliest proponents of Panamanian reggae, performing some of the first Spanish-language reggae tracks. This direct link between Jamaica and Panama and the embrace of reggae produced a different ecology that than in Puerto Rico, to where the genre arrived indirectly as mediated by New York and hip-hop. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Since the 1980s dancehall reggae has dominanted the scene through the consistent production of Spanish-language cover versions of contemporary reggae hits, typically over replayed versions of the original Jamaican riddims (see below for El General's cover of Shabba Ranks's \"Dem Bow\"). In this sense, Panamanian reggae is more of an emulation of dancehall, whereas Puerto Rican reggaetón is a reggae-derived music. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "align": "left",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "uuid": "5bc79b8d-3f44-4ad8-9682-f98ade0845c8",
      "includes": [
        "media",
        "annotations",
        "label",
        "description"
      ],
      "type": "event",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "uuid": "30d274e5-6f11-43a0-a211-10ffdd038147",
      "includes": [
        "media",
        "annotations",
        "label",
        "description"
      ],
      "type": "event",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "These reverent remakes would play a strong role in shaping the dancehall scene in Puerto Rico. The Columbia Records production "
        },
        {
          "text": "Dancehall Reggaespañol",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " (1991) emphasized the role cover versions played in reggaetón production by pairing \"Spanish reggae\" with Jamaican recordings. Also such versioning is consistent with the reggae tradition in general and had been in Panama for some time; the use of such riddims in New York was facilitated by producer Karl Miller. The tracks on "
        },
        {
          "text": "Dancehall Reggaespañol",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": " not only attest to a close engagement with contemporary Jamaican reggae, but also bear witness to the crucial role New York played in shaping reggaetón production. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
