    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Meren-Rap ",
          "textSize": "heading-three"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "These performances found their way to Puerto Rico via DJ Negro, who began operating The Noise nightclub in 1990, and the producer Jorge Oquendo's \"meren-rap\" project. This brought together rising Puerto Rican rap stars and established merengue musicians in a calculated attempt to develop a Latin pop/rap hybrid that could appeal to a wider audience of rap, reggae, merengue, pop, freestyle, and other Latin and urban dance genres (most of which were produced by Vico C). \"Te Ves Buena Remix\", a sample-based hip-hop inflected atempt at a reggae style track, is perhaps the closest of the project to sound like the productions soon to emerge from the parallel, grassroots development of rap-reggae fusions in San Juan. "
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
